      FTX flailing
   =20
 =20

One thing we know is that, as his crypto exchange FTX and his trading firm =
Alameda Research were spiraling into bankruptcy, Sam Bankman-Fried was desp=
erately shopping all of their assets to potential bidders to try to keep th=
em afloat. We also know what the list of assets looked like, and it was pre=
tty grisly. =E2=80=9CHello, we have $2.2 billion worth of Serum tokens, do =
you want them,=E2=80=9D Bankman-Fried apparently=C2=A0asked potential rescu=
ers, but the correct answer was =E2=80=9Cabsolutely not.=E2=80=9D The list =
was a lot of venture-capital stakes and weird illiquid tokens that FTX had =
made up,=C2=A0stuff like that.
  [1]

The most conventionally attractive thing on the list =E2=80=94=C2=A0the big=
gest line item in the =E2=80=9Cliquid=E2=80=9D column of the list of assets=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0was $472 million of =E2=80=9CHOOD,=E2=80=9D meaning the 7.6=
% stake in Robinhood Markets Inc. that Bankman-Fried bought in May.=C2=A0Te=
chnically those shares were owned by a vehicle named Emergent Fidelity Tech=
nologies Inc., which in turn was majority owned by Bankman-Fried and seems =
not to have had any official relationship with FTX or Alameda. (It did not =
file for bankruptcy with FTX this month.) But in the scramble to save his b=
usinesses, Bankman-Fried was willing to offer whatever he had, including th=
e Robinhood shares that he owned personally.
But he wanted good value for them. One easy=C2=A0thing that Bankman-Fried c=
ould have done was just call up his brokers and tell them to sell his Robin=
hood stock in the open market; Robinhood is publicly traded and fairly liqu=
id and this would have raised some cash. But it wouldn=E2=80=99t have raise=
d that=C2=A0much=C2=A0cash:=C2=A0Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s stake represents a=
bout five days=E2=80=99 trading volume of Robinhood, and if he had dumped i=
t quickly it would have crushed the price and raised only a few hundred mil=
lion dollars. FTX had something like $8 billion of missing customer money; =
the Robinhood cash, on its own, was hardly worth mentioning.
Instead it would have been more useful=C2=A0to offer the Robinhood shares a=
s the most attractive, liquid, normal asset in a bigger package of stuff to=
 a potential rescuer, and that is what Bankman-Fried seems to have done. =
=E2=80=9CHere=E2=80=99s a list of stuff, will you give us a few billion dol=
lars for this list of stuff? Look! The top thing on the list is this nice c=
lean Robinhood stake. Okay that=E2=80=99s enough looking.=E2=80=9D You take=
 a wad of crumpled $1 bills and $3 bills and dry cleaning receipts and chew=
ing-gum wrappers, you wrap some crisp $20s around the outside, you hold the=
 wad up in front of people and=C2=A0see what they=E2=80=99ll give you for i=
t. This seems perfectly reasonable.
Obviously the best outcome here is you find a well-capitalized=C2=A0rescuer=
 who agrees to backstop all of FTX=E2=80=99s customer accounts in exchange =
for a bag of miscellanea; Bankman-Fried sort of almost   accomplished that =
(with Binance Holdings Ltd.) but the deal fell through. (Apparently after B=
inance spent five minutes   looking inside=C2=A0the bag.) Failing that, sel=
ling the Robinhood stake at fire-sale prices in order to cash out customer =
withdrawals is not that great an outcome: It doesn=E2=80=99t raise that muc=
h cash, it signals panic, and it encourages=C2=A0a run on the bank, as cust=
omers say =E2=80=9Cwell I=E2=80=99d better cash out now while the Robinhood=
 money is there.=E2=80=9D
A middle ground =E2=80=94=C2=A0not as good as a deep-pocketed whole-company=
 rescue, but better than selling the shares piecemeal for=C2=A0some cash to=
 throw on the fire=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0is to use the Robinhood shares to=C2=
=A0reassure=C2=A0creditors. =E2=80=9CLook, your money is safe with FTX, we =
have all these nice Robinhood shares, they will cover our debt to you.=E2=
=80=9D You could do that in various informal ways =E2=80=94=C2=A0you could =
just=C2=A0say=C2=A0it, to the creditors, on the phone =E2=80=94=C2=A0or you=
 could do it formally, by pledging the Robinhood shares as collateral to th=
e creditors. =E2=80=9CDon=E2=80=99t withdraw your money now, look, we will =
hand over our Robinhood shares to make you feel better about keeping your m=
oney here.=E2=80=9D
Once you do that, though, you might be tempted to =E2=80=A6=C2=A0do it =E2=
=80=A6=C2=A0twice? The most efficient use of the Robinhood shares is to tel=
l=C2=A0each=C2=A0creditor =E2=80=9Cdon=E2=80=99t withdraw your money now, l=
ook, we have these Robinhood shares, they will cover our debt to you.=E2=80=
=9D They won=E2=80=99t cover FTX/Alameda=E2=80=99s debt to=C2=A0everyone! B=
ut if you say it to everyone=C2=A0privately, it might keep things going for=
 a while.
Meanwhile you keep shopping the shares for a whole-company rescue, etc.
At FT Alphaville, Kadhim Shubber, Antoine Gara and Alexandra Scaggs report:

Bankrupt cryptocurrency lender BlockFi is suing Sam Bankman-Fried to seize =
shares in Robinhood that the FTX founder allegedly pledged as collateral ju=
st days before his exchange collapsed.
The lawsuit on Monday came just hours after BlockFi filed for bankruptcy pr=
otection having suffered =E2=80=9Ca severe liquidity crunch=E2=80=9D trigge=
red by the failure of Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s FTX exchange.

Here is the complaint. Here is BlockFi Inc.=E2=80=99s first-day declaration=
 in its bankruptcy case, also filed yesterday. Based on those documents, th=
e timeline seems to be:
=09BlockFi has been a longtime lender to Alameda, Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s t=
rading firm, and as of early November had about $680 million of loans outst=
anding to Alameda. These loans were =E2=80=9Ccollateralized,=E2=80=9D accor=
ding to BlockFi=E2=80=99s declaration, though it is not clear by=C2=A0what;=
 nothing great, anyway, is the sense you get from these filings.=09Over the=
 summer, BlockFi had its own liquidity crisis, and agreed to a bailout from=
 FTX that included a $400 million line of credit. As of early November, Blo=
ckFi had drawn $275 million of that line.
  [2]

=09FTX fell apart in the blink of an eye on Monday and Tuesday, Nov. 7 and =
8. By Tuesday morning it had an agreement in principle to be bailed out by =
Binance; by Wednesday, Nov. 9,=C2=A0that deal was dead.=09BlockFi was watch=
ing this with interest. On Tuesday the 8th, it called up FTX and, somewhat =
hilariously, asked to draw down=C2=A0the last $125 million on its credit li=
ne. FTX, unsurprisingly, said no.
  [3]

=09Meanwhile, though, Alameda owed BlockFi about $680 million, and BlockFi =
apparently had the right to demand=C2=A0that=C2=A0money back. (And to forec=
lose on whatever collateral it had.) That was a bigger problem than the cre=
dit line: It would look a little bad for FTX to fail to fund its rescue of =
BlockFi, but it would be much worse for Alameda to either (1) ship off $680=
 million of scarce cash to BlockFi or (2) default on its debt.=09So Alameda=
 asked for more time, and Bankman-Fried bargained for more time by offering=
 his Robinhood shares.=09On Wednesday the 9th, BlockFi and Alameda entered =
a forbearance agreement, in which BlockFi gave Alameda more time to pay off=
 its loans. And in exchange, BlockFi and Emergent Fidelity (Bankman-Fried=
=E2=80=99s Robinhood vehicle) signed a pledge agreement, under which =E2=80=
=9CEmergent absolutely, unconditionally, and irrevocably guaranteed the pay=
ment obligations of the borrower under the Forbearance Agreement. Emergent=
=E2=80=99s guaranty was secured by a first priority security interest=E2=80=
=94in favor of BlockFi=E2=80=94in all of Emergent=E2=80=99s rights, titles,=
 and interests in, among other things, the collateral described in the Pled=
ge Agreement, including certain shares of common stock=E2=80=9D of Robinhoo=
d.=09This bought FTX/Alameda, you know, 20 minutes of breathing room? By We=
dnesday afternoon, the Binance rescue was dead, and by Thursday Bankman-Fri=
ed was sending around his desperation spreadsheet listing FTX/Alameda=E2=80=
=99s bag of miscellanea=C2=A0to try to find a bailout.=09By Thursday, Nov. =
10, the forbearance agreement was also dead: BlockFi =E2=80=9Cnotified Emer=
gent that the forbearance period had ended due to an event of default, incl=
uding borrower=E2=80=99s failure to timely make a required payment in accor=
dance with the payment schedule.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=09By Friday, Nov. 11, Bankm=
an-Fried=E2=80=99s rescue efforts came to an end=C2=A0and FTX filed for ban=
kruptcy.=09Now BlockFi would like to seize the Robinhood shares and sell th=
em, but Emergent Fidelity=E2=80=99s broker has said no.
  [4]



You will notice that Bankman-Fried was shopping the bag of miscellanea=C2=
=A0after=C2=A0pledging the Robinhood shares to BlockFi, and that the bag of=
 miscellanea that he was shopping very much included those Robinhood shares=
. These things happen! FT Alphaville:

Earlier in November, the FT reported that Bankman-Fried had been privately =
attempting to sell the Robinhood shares using the secure messaging app Sign=
al in the days leading up to FTX=E2=80=99s bankruptcy filing on November 11=
.
Bankman-Fried had continued to negotiate selling his Robinhood shares even =
after entering into the pledge agreement, according to two people familiar =
with the matter.
According to messages seen by the FT, Bankman-Fried was still negotiating t=
hose sales on the evening of November 10.

I have to say that I can sympathize? Of course it is=C2=A0bad. Like, if he=
=C2=A0had=C2=A0succeeded in finding a buyer for the Robinhood shares, and t=
hen the buyer found out that they were already pledged to BlockFi, that wou=
ld have been an embarrassing mix-up, and could have killed the deal. But:
=09If he had succeeded in finding a whole-company=C2=A0rescuer, someone to =
take on all of Alameda/FTX=E2=80=99s obligations, then BlockFi would have g=
otten paid and everything would have been=C2=A0fine. This did not happen, a=
nd I cannot say it looked all that=C2=A0likely=C2=A0at the time, but I gues=
s it was worth a shot.=09In hindsight Bankman-Fried did not=C2=A0get=C2=A0v=
ery much for pledging those Robinhood shares to BlockFi. BlockFi held off o=
n calling in the Alameda loan for something like 24 hours. At the beginning=
 of those 24 hours, that delay probably looked very valuable to Bankman-Fri=
ed (he had 24 hours to save his company!); by the end, it did not (he had n=
ot saved his company!). So you can see why he would want a do-over to try t=
o get some more bang for his buck on the Robinhood shares.=C2=A0

I don=E2=80=99t know who will win here, by the way; I suppose it turns on q=
uestions about perfecting security interests in stock and avoidable prefere=
nces in bankruptcy. It does seem a little unfair that BlockFi would get a p=
riority claim on these shares, over the claims of=C2=A0FTX=E2=80=99s custom=
ers, just because Bankman-Fried hastily promised them to BlockFi; there is =
some sense =E2=80=94=C2=A0both in fairness and in the bankruptcy code=C2=A0=
=E2=80=94=C2=A0that stuff that Bankman-Fried did in those final desperate d=
ays before bankruptcy shouldn=E2=80=99t really count.=C2=A0
Mostly it is just a wild story. FTX and Alameda were hurtling toward bankru=
ptcy, and Bankman-Fried was trying to save them by offering up his one norm=
al asset, a pile of=C2=A0Robinhood shares. He tried to get the most value h=
e could from those shares, to use them most efficiently to save his compani=
es. Obviously the most efficient way to use them was to sell them more than=
 once!

