      Further FTX flailing
   =20
 =20

The basic idea of bankruptcy is that if your company doesn=E2=80=99t have e=
nough money to pay all of its debts, it should stop paying its debts, get a=
ll its creditors in a room, and work out how to pay each of them a fair amo=
unt. If you have $100 of debt and $60 of assets, generally, it is good to p=
ay each of your creditors 60 cents on the dollar, and bad to pay 100 cents =
on the dollar to the first creditors who ask for their money back, and then=
 run out of money and pay everyone else $0.=C2=A0
If you run a business where you have hundreds of thousands of creditors, al=
l of whom can demand their money back at any time by pushing a button on yo=
ur website, this is a particular problem. Once you don=E2=80=99t have enoug=
h money to pay all of them back, it is bad form to keep the website up. Som=
e people will push the button and get their money back, leaving less and le=
ss for everyone else. This will make your eventual bankruptcy messier, and =
might violate your fiduciary duties.
  [5]
=C2=A0Also if you do this then that will=C2=A0cause=C2=A0people to ask for =
their money back,=C2=A0if they figure out that they are in a race with your=
 other creditors.=C2=A0If people are asking for their money back, and you d=
on=E2=80=99t have enough for all of them, you really ought to shut down the=
 website as soon as possible.
On the other hand if you shut the website down it is =E2=80=A6=C2=A0hard to=
 recover from that? Like, if you have $100 of debt and assets that have fal=
len to $95 and people start taking their money out, you might be tempted to=
 (1) give them their money when they ask, (2) keep the website up, (3) twee=
t =E2=80=9Ceverything is fine,=E2=80=9D and (4) hope the value of your asse=
ts goes back up before too many people take their money out. One of the cla=
ssic remedies=C2=A0for a run on the bank is=C2=A0acting really really reall=
y confident. Sometimes it works! Sometimes it doesn=E2=80=99t! Hard to know=
 until you try. If you shut down the website, then you are pretty much cons=
igning yourself to bankruptcy and paying everyone 95 cents on the dollar (m=
inus huge legal fees). If you keep the website up and tweet confidently, ma=
ybe everything will be fine and everyone will get 100 cents on the dollar a=
nd you can keep running the company.
Which path you choose will depend on the facts of the situation, but also o=
n your personality type and training and personal incentives. For instance:
=09If you are a financial services lawyer, you will have a bias toward shut=
ting down and filing for bankruptcy earlier rather than later. Sorry! The t=
hing about lawyers being risk-averse is largely true.=09If you were a trade=
r at a high-frequency market-making firm, trained to maximize edge and take=
 risk-neutral gambles, and if you left that firm because you wanted to take=
 more risk in your personal life, and if you yourself have a particularly  =
idiosyncratic view of which gambles are good, and if you have gone around t=
elling interviewers that you will always take a risky gamble that maximizes=
 expected value, even a =E2=80=9C51% [chance] you double the earth out some=
where else, 49% it all disappears=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0you=E2=80=99re go=
nna keep the website up and tweet confidently.
  [6]
=C2=A0=09If you own billions of dollars of=C2=A0equity=C2=A0in the business=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0which will be worth zero in bankruptcy, but might be worth =
billions of dollars again if you muddle through =E2=80=94=C2=A0you will wan=
t to keep the website up.

Perhaps=C2=A0no one in the history of finance has been more predisposed to =
gamble on redemption than Sam Bankman-Fried, but his lawyers disagreed.  Th=
e New York Times reports:

As the crisis unfolded, a group of FTX lawyers and executives moved to stri=
p authority from Mr. Bankman-Fried and urged the company=E2=80=99s top lead=
ers to prepare for bankruptcy. For days, Mr. Bankman-Fried ignored their wa=
rnings and clung to power, seemingly convinced that he could save the firm,=
 despite mounting evidence to the contrary.
=E2=80=9CThe exchanges must be halted immediately,=E2=80=9D Ryne Miller, a =
top FTX lawyer, wrote in an email to Mr. Bankman-Fried and other staff on N=
ov. 10. =E2=80=9CThe founding team is not currently in a cooperative postur=
e.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6
While Mr. Bankman-Fried was scrambling to line up investors, Mr. Miller sen=
t a text to top staff describing the prospect of a fund-raise as =E2=80=9C0=
% likelihood.=E2=80=9D
The push and pull continued into the early hours of Nov. 11, when Mr. Mille=
r sent a series of messages urging Mr. Bankman-Fried to sign papers so the =
company could file for bankruptcy.
=E2=80=9CPlease can you sign the document,=E2=80=9D he wrote at 2:29 a.m. =
=E2=80=A6
[Wednesday] afternoon [Nov. 9],=C2=A0Mr. Miller asked Mr. Bankman-Fried and=
 two other executives to shut down trading on FTX=E2=80=99s platforms. =E2=
=80=9CWho can turn off the websites?=E2=80=9D he asked in a group chat at 4=
:41 p.m. Two minutes later, he got a response from Constance Wang, FTX=E2=
=80=99s chief operating officer and one of Mr. Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s top =
lieutenants.
=E2=80=9CRyne, I love you,=E2=80=9D she wrote, =E2=80=9Cbut I don=E2=80=99t=
 want to stop trying yet.=E2=80=9D

That checks out: The risk-neutral traders wanted to keep trying; the lawyer=
 did not. I have to say that the likelihood of a rescue on Nov. 10   struck=
 me as =E2=80=A6=C2=A0very very close to 0% =E2=80=A6=C2=A0but then I was t=
rained as a lawyer and did=C2=A0not=C2=A0quit my job to move to an island a=
nd start a crypto exchange. Nor did I quit my job to become a top lawyer fo=
r someone who had done that! Seems stressful.

