      Customer money
   =20
 =20

I have been thinking a lot, these days, about   my 2018 proposal for a =E2=
=80=9CCertificate of Dumb Investment.=E2=80=9D The way it would work is tha=
t there are certain kinds of investment =E2=80=94=C2=A0at the time I was ma=
inly thinking of private placements =E2=80=94=C2=A0where anyone can invest =
as much money as they want, but:
=09First you have to go to a local office of the Securities and Exchange Co=
mmission and ask for a certificate.=09To get the certificate, you have to s=
ign a one-page form that says, in large letters, that your investment is du=
mb and you will almost certainly get all of your money stolen and you can=
=E2=80=99t complain when that happens.=09Then an SEC employee =E2=80=9Cslap=
s you hard across the face and says =E2=80=98really???=E2=80=99=C2=A0And if=
 you reply =E2=80=98yes really=E2=80=99 then she gives you the certificate.=
=E2=80=9D=09Then you give the certificate to the seller of the investment a=
nd you get to buy it.=09=E2=80=9CIf an article ever appears in the Wall Str=
eet Journal in which you (or your lawyer) are quoted saying that you were j=
ust a simple dentist, didn=E2=80=99t understand what you were buying and we=
re swindled by the seller=E2=80=99s flashy sales pitch, then you go to pris=
on.=E2=80=9D

This seems unlikely to become the law, but I still think it=E2=80=99s a goo=
d idea.
I would not exactly say that crypto has built this system. Lots of entrepre=
neurs=C2=A0in crypto (1) do conventional things to make themselves seem sta=
ble, conservative and trustworthy and then (2) lose or steal their customer=
s=E2=80=99 money. Still, though, the=C2=A0atmosphere=C2=A0in crypto is so s=
uffused with hacks, scams=C2=A0and Ponzis that it is=C2=A0hard=C2=A0=E2=80=
=94=C2=A0not impossible! but hard =E2=80=94=C2=A0not to know what you=E2=80=
=99re getting into. And so, when a crypto exchange loses its customers=E2=
=80=99=C2=A0money, the customers=E2=80=99=C2=A0reaction tends to be less =
=E2=80=9CI can=E2=80=99t believe a crypto exchange lost my life savings=E2=
=80=9D and more=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cwell I put my gambling money there because I=
=C2=A0thought that it was a relatively trustworthy crypto exchange, but, yo=
u know.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Anyway BlockFi Inc. froze customer deposits earlier this month=C2=A0and fil=
ed for bankruptcy yesterday, and=C2=A0Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Claire Ballentine=
 and Paulina Cachero dutifully   rounded up quotes from customers whose mon=
ey is gone, and the customers are all like =E2=80=9Cwell yes obviously=E2=
=80=9D:

Others are trying to accept their losses and move on, despite the lost mone=
y. That=E2=80=99s the case for William Casey.=C2=A0
At first, he ignored the warning signs in the digital asset space.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CWhen you follow crypto for long enough, you get calloused to the t=
hreat of loss,=E2=80=9D the Texas-based trader said. ...
It doesn=E2=80=99t quite feel real for him yet, and he=E2=80=99s taking a =
=E2=80=9Cwait-and-see approach.=E2=80=9D He said he=E2=80=99s been investin=
g in crypto since 2013 and has made more than $400,000 over the years.=C2=
=A0
=E2=80=9CThis life-changing amount of money was so easy come, easy go that =
I can=E2=80=99t help but feel disassociated from it,=E2=80=9D Casey said. =
=E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m just kind of letting things happen =E2=80=94 it would =
be nice if we got our money back, but right now it=E2=80=99s just a kind of=
 quiet resignation.=E2=80=9D

And:

He was putting regular deposits into BlockFi=E2=80=99s interest-bearing acc=
ounts to sit and appreciate, enticed by yields as high as 9.75%. Although h=
e knew keeping his savings in crypto was a =E2=80=9Cgamble,=E2=80=9D he bel=
ieved BlockFi was safer than other platforms since it was based in the US.=
=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CIf Bitcoin just dropped to zero, that would be one thing,=E2=80=9D=
 he said. =E2=80=9CBut now it feels like some kid just stole my money and i=
t doesn=E2=80=99t sit well with me.=E2=80=9D

=E2=80=9CBlockFi Bankruptcy Hijacks More Customer Cash,=E2=80=9D is the hea=
dline. Here we go again.
Obviously this is an=C2=A0imperfect=C2=A0system, both in the sense that som=
ewhere out there there probably are=C2=A0less sophisticated investors who g=
enuinely thought that the accounts paying 9.75% interest on cryptocurrency =
were safe, and in the sense that lots of crypto platforms =E2=80=94=C2=A0in=
cluding both FTX and BlockFi =E2=80=94=C2=A0tried to give off an air of leg=
itimacy and trustworthiness that might have led people to think =E2=80=9Cth=
is time is different,=C2=A0these=C2=A0platforms won=E2=80=99t lose my money=
.=E2=80=9D The damage here is not=C2=A0zero.
But it is=C2=A0hard, particularly in the US, to find people who (1) know en=
ough about crypto to be able to buy it but (2) know so little about crypto =
that they are surprised when a crypto=C2=A0exchange loses their money. Cryp=
to does a pretty good job =E2=80=94=C2=A0not on purpose or anything, but ne=
vertheless =E2=80=94=C2=A0of educating its investors about how they will lo=
se their money. And then when it happens, they shrug and say =E2=80=9Ceasy =
come, easy go.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0

