<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">FTX flailing</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One thing we know is that, as his crypto excha=
nge FTX and his trading firm Alameda Research were spiraling into bankruptc=
y, Sam Bankman-Fried was desperately shopping all of their assets to potent=
ial bidders to try to keep them afloat. We also know <a href=3D"https://lin=
k.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29838293.272550/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21i=
ZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTEtMTQvZnR4LXMtYmFsYW5jZS1zaGVldC1=
3YXMtYmFkP2NtcGlkPUJCRDExMjkyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3=
NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMTEyOSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZ=
g/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd90f3f05" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"it=
emscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !=
important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-b=
ottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">what the list of assets looked=
 like</a>, and it was pretty grisly. =E2=80=9CHello, we have $2.2 billion w=
orth of Serum tokens, do you want them,=E2=80=9D Bankman-Fried apparently=
=C2=A0asked potential rescuers, but the correct answer was =E2=80=9Cabsolut=
ely not.=E2=80=9D The list was a lot of venture-capital stakes and weird il=
liquid tokens that FTX had made up,=C2=A0stuff like that.<a class=3D"footno=
te-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: no=
ne !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bord=
er-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important;=
 display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The most conventionally attractive thing on th=
e list =E2=80=94=C2=A0the biggest line item in the =E2=80=9Cliquid=E2=80=9D=
 column of the list of assets =E2=80=94=C2=A0was $472 million of =E2=80=9CH=
OOD,=E2=80=9D meaning the 7.6% stake in Robinhood Markets Inc. that Bankman=
-Fried <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29838293.27=
2550/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE3ODM4NzkvMDAwMT=
E0MDM2MTIyMDE4ODI3L2JyaGMxMDAzNzQ2NV9zYzEzZC5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB=
9e74b268" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgro=
und-color: #ccc;">bought in May</a>.=C2=A0Technically those shares were own=
ed by a vehicle named Emergent Fidelity Technologies Inc., which in turn wa=
s majority owned by Bankman-Fried and seems not to have had any official re=
lationship with FTX or Alameda. (It did not <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bl=
oombergbusiness.com/click/29838293.272550/aHR0cHM6Ly9yZXN0cnVjdHVyaW5nLnJhL=
mtyb2xsLmNvbS9GVFgvSG9tZS1Eb3dubG9hZFBERj9pZDE9TVRNMU1qTTNPUT09JmlkMj0tMQ/6=
07f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa7b65a7b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"items=
cope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">file for bankruptcy</a> with FTX =
this month.) But in the scramble to save his businesses, Bankman-Fried was =
willing to offer whatever he had, including the Robinhood shares that he ow=
ned personally.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But he wanted good value for them. One easy=C2=
=A0thing that Bankman-Fried could have done was just call up his brokers an=
d tell them to sell his Robinhood stock in the open market; Robinhood is pu=
blicly traded and fairly liquid and this would have raised some cash. But i=
t wouldn=E2=80=99t have raised that=C2=A0<em>much=C2=A0</em>cash:=C2=A0Bank=
man-Fried=E2=80=99s stake represents about five days=E2=80=99 trading volum=
e of Robinhood, and if he had dumped it quickly it would have crushed the p=
rice and raised only a few hundred million dollars. FTX had something like =
$8 billion of missing customer money; the Robinhood cash, on its own, was h=
ardly worth mentioning.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Instead it would have been more useful=C2=A0to=
 offer the Robinhood shares as the most attractive, liquid, normal asset in=
 a bigger package of stuff to a potential rescuer, and that is what Bankman=
-Fried seems to have done. =E2=80=9CHere=E2=80=99s a list of stuff, will yo=
u give us a few billion dollars for this list of stuff? Look! The top thing=
 on the list is this nice clean Robinhood stake. Okay that=E2=80=99s enough=
 looking.=E2=80=9D You take a wad of crumpled $1 bills and $3 bills and dry=
 cleaning receipts and chewing-gum wrappers, you wrap some crisp $20s aroun=
d the outside, you hold the wad up in front of people and=C2=A0see what the=
y=E2=80=99ll give you for it. This seems perfectly reasonable.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Obviously the best outcome here is you find a =
well-capitalized=C2=A0rescuer who agrees to backstop all of FTX=E2=80=99s c=
ustomer accounts in exchange for a bag of miscellanea; Bankman-Fried sort o=
f almost <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29838293.=
272550/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTEt=
MDgvYmluYW5jZS1zLXpoYW8tc2JmLWVkLWZ0eC1zLWJhbmttYW4tZnJpZWQ_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTE=
yOTIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdX=
RtX3Rlcm09MjIxMTI5JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23c=
B0da060dd" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgr=
ound-color: #ccc;">  accomplished that</a> (with Binance Holdings Ltd.) but=
 the deal fell through. (Apparently after Binance spent five minutes <a hre=
f=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29838293.272550/aHR0cHM6=
Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTEtMTAvZnR4LWlzLXN=
0aWxsLWxvb2tpbmctZm9yLW1vbmV5P2NtcGlkPUJCRDExMjkyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZW=
RpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMTEyOSZ1dG1fY2Ftc=
GFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf351f41c" itemprop=3D"StoryL=
ink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  looking =
inside=C2=A0the bag</a>.) Failing that, selling the Robinhood stake at fire=
-sale prices in order to cash out customer withdrawals is not that great an=
 outcome: It doesn=E2=80=99t raise that much cash, it signals panic, and it=
 <em>encourages=C2=A0</em>a run on the bank, as customers say =E2=80=9Cwell=
 I=E2=80=99d better cash out now while the Robinhood money is there.=E2=80=
=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A middle ground =E2=80=94=C2=A0not as good as =
a deep-pocketed whole-company rescue, but better than selling the shares pi=
ecemeal for=C2=A0some cash to throw on the fire=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0is to u=
se the Robinhood shares to=C2=A0<em>reassure=C2=A0</em>creditors. =E2=80=9C=
Look, your money is safe with FTX, we have all these nice Robinhood shares,=
 they will cover our debt to you.=E2=80=9D You could do that in various inf=
ormal ways =E2=80=94=C2=A0you could just=C2=A0<em>say=C2=A0</em>it, to the =
creditors, on the phone =E2=80=94=C2=A0or you could do it formally, by pled=
ging the Robinhood shares as collateral to the creditors. =E2=80=9CDon=E2=
=80=99t withdraw your money now, look, we will hand over our Robinhood shar=
es to make you feel better about keeping your money here.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Once you do that, though, you might be tempted=
 to =E2=80=A6=C2=A0do it =E2=80=A6=C2=A0twice? The most efficient use of th=
e Robinhood shares is to tell=C2=A0<em>each=C2=A0</em>creditor =E2=80=9Cdon=
=E2=80=99t withdraw your money now, look, we have these Robinhood shares, t=
hey will cover our debt to you.=E2=80=9D They won=E2=80=99t cover FTX/Alame=
da=E2=80=99s debt to=C2=A0<em>everyone</em>! But if you say it to everyone=
=C2=A0<em>privately</em>, it might keep things going for a while.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile you keep shopping the shares for a w=
hole-company rescue, etc.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At FT Alphaville, <a href=3D"https://link.mail=
.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29838293.272550/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2Nvbn=
RlbnQvMTcxOWUxMjItM2I1MC00ZDg2LTlhMzAtOWZlNzJmMjI4NmZl/607f07ceef4b8524a319=
a23cBe0fd59aa" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bl=
ank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; ba=
ckground-color: #ccc;">Kadhim Shubber, Antoine Gara and Alexandra Scaggs re=
port</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bankrupt cryptocurrency lender BlockFi is suin=
g Sam Bankman-Fried to seize shares in Robinhood that the FTX founder alleg=
edly pledged as collateral just days before his exchange collapsed.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The lawsuit on Monday came just hours after Bl=
ockFi filed for bankruptcy protection having suffered =E2=80=9Ca severe liq=
uidity crunch=E2=80=9D triggered by the failure of Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s =
FTX exchange.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/29838293.272550/aHR0cHM6Ly9wYWNlci1kb2N1bWVudHMuczMuYW1h=
em9uYXdzLmNvbS8xMDkvMTA5NDA3OC8xMTgxNjQyMDE5MDMucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a2=
3cB68224f8d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blan=
k" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;">the complaint</a>. Here is BlockFi Inc.=E2=80=99s <a h=
ref=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29838293.272550/aHR0cH=
M6Ly9hc3NldHMuYndieC5pby9kb2N1bWVudHMvdXNlcnMvaXFqV0hCRmRmeElVL3JCNmIzZFhMV=
DM3OC92MA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1573bd9b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsco=
pe=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration=
: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; =
border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">first-day declaration<=
/a> in its bankruptcy case, also filed yesterday. Based on those documents,=
 the timeline seems to be:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">BlockFi has been a longtime lender to =
Alameda, Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s trading firm, and as of early November had=
 about $680 million of loans outstanding to Alameda. These loans were =E2=
=80=9Ccollateralized,=E2=80=9D according to BlockFi=E2=80=99s declaration, =
though it is not clear by=C2=A0<em>what</em>; nothing great, anyway, is the=
 sense you get from these filings.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;"=
>Over the summer, BlockFi had its own liquidity crisis, and agreed to a bai=
lout from FTX that included a $400 million line of credit. As of early Nove=
mber, BlockFi had drawn $275 million of that line.<a class=3D"footnote-inde=
x" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; displa=
y: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">FTX fell apart in the blink of an=
 eye on Monday and Tuesday, Nov. 7 and 8. By Tuesday morning it had an agre=
ement in principle to be <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com=
/click/29838293.272550/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGlj=
bGVzLzIwMjItMTEtMDgvYmluYW5jZS1zLXpoYW8tc2JmLWVkLWZ0eC1zLWJhbmttYW4tZnJpZWQ=
_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTEyOTIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW=
5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIxMTI5JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ce=
ef4b8524a319a23cC0da060dd" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" t=
arget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: solid; background-color: #ccc;">bailed out by Binance</a>; by Wednesday,=
 Nov. 9,=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2983=
8293.272550/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTE=
tMDkvYmluYW5jZS1zZWVuLWxpa2VseS10by1iYWxrLWF0LWZ0eC1kZWFsLWFmdGVyLXNwb3R0aW=
5nLWRlZXAtaG9sZT9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMTI5MjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJ=
nV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjExMjkmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5=
c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc35e57e0" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">that deal was dead</a>.<=
/li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">BlockFi was watching this with int=
erest. On Tuesday the 8th, it called up FTX and, somewhat hilariously, aske=
d to draw down=C2=A0the last $125 million on its credit line. FTX, unsurpri=
singly, said no.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"c=
olor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; =
border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; backgro=
und-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Meanwhile, though, Alameda owed B=
lockFi about $680 million, and BlockFi apparently had the right to demand=
=C2=A0<em>that=C2=A0</em>money back. (And to foreclose on whatever collater=
al it had.) That was a bigger problem than the credit line: It would look a=
 little bad for FTX to fail to fund its rescue of BlockFi, but it would be =
much worse for Alameda to either (1) ship off $680 million of scarce cash t=
o BlockFi or (2) default on its debt.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5p=
x;">So Alameda asked for more time, and Bankman-Fried bargained for more ti=
me by offering his Robinhood shares.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px=
;">On Wednesday the 9th, BlockFi and Alameda entered a forbearance agreemen=
t, in which BlockFi gave Alameda more time to pay off its loans. And in exc=
hange, BlockFi and Emergent Fidelity (Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s Robinhood veh=
icle) signed a pledge agreement, under which =E2=80=9CEmergent absolutely, =
unconditionally, and irrevocably guaranteed the payment obligations of the =
borrower under the Forbearance Agreement. Emergent=E2=80=99s guaranty was s=
ecured by a first priority security interest=E2=80=94in favor of BlockFi=E2=
=80=94in all of Emergent=E2=80=99s rights, titles, and interests in, among =
other things, the collateral described in the Pledge Agreement, including c=
ertain shares of common stock=E2=80=9D of Robinhood.</li>=09<li style=3D"ma=
rgin-bottom: 5px;">This bought FTX/Alameda, you know, 20 minutes of breathi=
ng room? By Wednesday afternoon, the Binance rescue was dead, and by Thursd=
ay Bankman-Fried was sending around his desperation spreadsheet listing FTX=
/Alameda=E2=80=99s bag of miscellanea=C2=A0to <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/29838293.272550/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmN=
vbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTEtMTAvZnR4LWlzLXN0aWxsLWxvb2tpbmctZm9yLW=
1vbmV5P2NtcGlkPUJCRDExMjkyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3Nvd=
XJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMTEyOSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/6=
07f07ceef4b8524a319a23cCf351f41c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"items=
cope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">try to find a bailout</a>.</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">By Thursday, Nov. 10, the forbearance =
agreement was also dead: BlockFi =E2=80=9Cnotified Emergent that the forbea=
rance period had ended due to an event of default, including borrower=E2=80=
=99s failure to timely make a required payment in accordance with the payme=
nt schedule.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">By Fri=
day, Nov. 11, Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s rescue efforts came to an end=C2=A0an=
d FTX filed for bankruptcy.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Now Bl=
ockFi would like to seize the Robinhood shares and sell them, but Emergent =
Fidelity=E2=80=99s broker has said no.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#=
footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: no=
ne !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-bl=
ock;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>
</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You will notice that Bankman-Fried was shoppin=
g the bag of miscellanea=C2=A0<em>after=C2=A0</em>pledging the Robinhood sh=
ares to BlockFi, and that the bag of miscellanea that he was shopping very =
much included those Robinhood shares. These things happen! FT Alphaville:</=
p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Earlier in November, the FT reported that Bank=
man-Fried had been privately attempting to sell the Robinhood shares using =
the secure messaging app Signal in the days leading up to FTX=E2=80=99s ban=
kruptcy filing on November 11.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bankman-Fried had continued to negotiate selli=
ng his Robinhood shares even after entering into the pledge agreement, acco=
rding to two people familiar with the matter.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">According to messages seen by the FT, Bankman-=
Fried was still negotiating those sales on the evening of November 10.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I have to say that I can sympathize? Of course=
 it is=C2=A0<em>bad</em>. Like, if he=C2=A0<em>had=C2=A0</em>succeeded in f=
inding a buyer for the Robinhood shares, and then the buyer found out that =
they were already pledged to BlockFi, that would have been an embarrassing =
mix-up, and could have killed the deal. But:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If he had succeeded in finding a <em>=
whole-company=C2=A0rescuer</em>, someone to take on all of Alameda/FTX=E2=
=80=99s obligations, then BlockFi would have gotten paid and everything wou=
ld have been=C2=A0fine. This did not happen, and I cannot say it looked all=
 that=C2=A0<em>likely=C2=A0</em>at the time, but I guess it was worth a sho=
t.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">In hindsight Bankman-Fried did =
not=C2=A0<em>get=C2=A0</em>very much for pledging those Robinhood shares to=
 BlockFi. BlockFi held off on calling in the Alameda loan for something lik=
e 24 hours. At the beginning of those 24 hours, that delay probably looked =
very valuable to Bankman-Fried (he had 24 hours to save his company!); by t=
he end, it did not (he had not saved his company!). So you can see why he w=
ould want a do-over to try to get some more bang for his buck on the Robinh=
ood shares.=C2=A0</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t know who will win here, by the=
 way; I suppose it turns on questions about perfecting security interests i=
n stock and avoidable preferences in bankruptcy. It does seem a little unfa=
ir that BlockFi would get a priority claim on these shares, over the claims=
 of=C2=A0FTX=E2=80=99s customers, just because Bankman-Fried hastily promis=
ed them to BlockFi; there is some sense =E2=80=94=C2=A0both in fairness and=
 in <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29838293.27255=
0/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubGF3LmNvcm5lbGwuZWR1L3VzY29kZS90ZXh0LzExLzU0Nw/607f07ceef=
4b8524a319a23cB5342dcc0" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" tar=
get=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;">the bankruptcy code</a>=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=
=A0that stuff that Bankman-Fried did in those final desperate days before b=
ankruptcy shouldn=E2=80=99t really count.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Mostly it is just a wild story. FTX and Alamed=
a were hurtling toward bankruptcy, and Bankman-Fried was trying to save the=
m by offering up his one normal asset, a pile of=C2=A0Robinhood shares. He =
tried to get the most value he could from those shares, to use them most ef=
ficiently to save his companies. Obviously the most efficient way to use th=
em was to sell them more than once!</p>
