<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Further FTX flailing</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The basic idea of bankruptcy is that if your c=
ompany doesn=E2=80=99t have enough money to pay all of its debts, it should=
 stop paying its debts, get all its creditors in a room, and work out how t=
o pay each of them a fair amount. If you have $100 of debt and $60 of asset=
s, generally, it is good to pay each of your creditors 60 cents on the doll=
ar, and bad to pay 100 cents on the dollar to the first creditors who ask f=
or their money back, and then run out of money and pay everyone else $0.=C2=
=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you run a business where you have <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29838293.272550/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuY25iYy5jb20vMjAyMi8xMS8xNS9mdHgtc2F5cy1jb3VsZC1oYXZlLW92ZXItMS1taWxs=
aW9uLWNyZWRpdG9ycy1pbi1uZXctYmFua3J1cHRjeS1maWxpbmcuaHRtbA/607f07ceef4b8524=
a319a23cB7c6139cd" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D=
"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid=
; background-color: #ccc;">hundreds of thousands of creditors</a>, all of w=
hom can demand their money back at any time by pushing a button on your web=
site, this is a particular problem. Once you don=E2=80=99t have enough mone=
y to pay all of them back, it is bad form to keep the website up. Some peop=
le will push the button and get their money back, leaving less and less for=
 everyone else. This will make your eventual bankruptcy messier, and might =
violate your fiduciary duties.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote=
-5" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-botto=
m-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !impo=
rtant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Also if you do this then that will=C2=A0<em>cause=C2=A0</em>peopl=
e to ask for their money back,=C2=A0if they figure out that they are in a r=
ace with your other creditors.=C2=A0If people are asking for their money ba=
ck, and you don=E2=80=99t have enough for all of them, you really ought to =
shut down the website as soon as possible.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the other hand if you shut the website down=
 it is =E2=80=A6=C2=A0hard to recover from that? Like, if you have $100 of =
debt and assets that have fallen to $95 and people start taking their money=
 out, you might be tempted to (1) give them their money when they ask, (2) =
keep the website up, (3) tweet =E2=80=9Ceverything is fine,=E2=80=9D and (4=
) hope the value of your assets goes back up before too many people take th=
eir money out. One of the classic remedies=C2=A0for a run on the bank is=C2=
=A0<em>acting really really really confident</em>. Sometimes it works! Some=
times it doesn=E2=80=99t! Hard to know until you try. If you shut down the =
website, then you are pretty much consigning yourself to bankruptcy and pay=
ing everyone 95 cents on the dollar (minus huge legal fees). If you keep th=
e website up and tweet confidently, maybe everything will be fine and every=
one will get 100 cents on the dollar and you can keep running the company.<=
/p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Which path you choose will depend on the facts=
 of the situation, but also on your personality type and training and perso=
nal incentives. For instance:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If you are a financial services lawye=
r, you will have a bias toward shutting down and filing for bankruptcy earl=
ier rather than later. Sorry! The thing about lawyers being risk-averse is =
largely true.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If you were a trader=
 at a high-frequency market-making firm, trained to maximize edge and take =
risk-neutral gambles, and if you left that firm because you wanted to take =
more risk in your personal life, and if you yourself have a particularly <a=
 href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29838293.272550/aHR0=
cHM6Ly93d3cudGhlZGlmZi5jby9wL21vbmV5LWNyZWRpdC10cnVzdC1mdHg/607f07ceef4b852=
4a319a23cBbb2b924e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;"> idiosyncratic view</a> of which gambles are =
good, and if you have <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cl=
ick/29838293.272550/aHR0cHM6Ly9lbG13ZWFsdGguY29tL2EtbWlzc2luZy1waWVjZS1vZi1=
0aGUtc2JmLXB1enpsZS8/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7bbdaff4" itemprop=3D"StoryLi=
nk" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">gone around=
 telling interviewers</a> that you will always take a risky gamble that max=
imizes expected value, even a =E2=80=9C51% [chance] you double the earth ou=
t somewhere else, 49% it all disappears=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0you=E2=80=
=99re gonna keep the website up and tweet confidently.<a class=3D"footnote-=
index" href=3D"#footnote-6" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; di=
splay: inline-block;">
<span>[6]</span>
</a>=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If you own billions of =
dollars of=C2=A0<em>equity=C2=A0</em>in the business =E2=80=94=C2=A0which w=
ill be worth zero in bankruptcy, but might be worth billions of dollars aga=
in if you muddle through =E2=80=94=C2=A0you will want to keep the website u=
p.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Perhaps=C2=A0no one in the history of finance =
has been more predisposed to gamble on redemption than Sam Bankman-Fried, b=
ut his lawyers disagreed. <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.co=
m/click/29838293.272550/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubnl0aW1lcy5jb20vMjAyMi8xMS8yOS90ZWN=
obm9sb2d5L3NhbS1iYW5rbWFuLWZyaWVkLWZ0eC1iYW5rcnVwdGN5Lmh0bWw/607f07ceef4b85=
24a319a23cBda99a944" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;"> The New York Times reports</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As the crisis unfolded, a group of FTX lawyers=
 and executives moved to strip authority from Mr. Bankman-Fried and urged t=
he company=E2=80=99s top leaders to prepare for bankruptcy. For days, Mr. B=
ankman-Fried ignored their warnings and clung to power, seemingly convinced=
 that he could save the firm, despite mounting evidence to the contrary.</p=
>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThe exchanges must be halted immediat=
ely,=E2=80=9D Ryne Miller, a top FTX lawyer, wrote in an email to Mr. Bankm=
an-Fried and other staff on Nov. 10. =E2=80=9CThe founding team is not curr=
ently in a cooperative posture.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">While Mr. Bankman-Fried was scrambling to line=
 up investors, Mr. Miller sent a text to top staff describing the prospect =
of a fund-raise as =E2=80=9C0% likelihood.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The push and pull continued into the early hou=
rs of Nov. 11, when Mr. Miller sent a series of messages urging Mr. Bankman=
-Fried to sign papers so the company could file for bankruptcy.</p>
