=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
  my 2018 proposal</a> for a =E2=80=9CCertificate of Dumb Investment.=E2=80=
=9D The way it would work is that there are certain kinds of investment =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0at the time I was mainly thinking of private placements =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0where anyone can invest as much money as they want, but:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">First you have to go to a local offic=
e of the Securities and Exchange Commission and ask for a certificate.</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">To get the certificate, you have to si=
gn a one-page form that says, in large letters, that your investment is dum=
b and you will almost certainly get all of your money stolen and you can=E2=
=80=99t complain when that happens.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;=
">Then an SEC employee =E2=80=9Cslaps you hard across the face and says =E2=
=80=98really???=E2=80=99=C2=A0And if you reply =E2=80=98yes really=E2=80=99=
 then she gives you the certificate.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bo=
ttom: 5px;">Then you give the certificate to the seller of the investment a=
nd you get to buy it.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">=E2=80=9CIf =
an article ever appears in the Wall Street Journal in which you (or your la=
wyer) are quoted saying that you were just a simple dentist, didn=E2=80=99t=
 understand what you were buying and were swindled by the seller=E2=80=99s =
flashy sales pitch, then <em>you</em> go to prison.=E2=80=9D</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This seems unlikely to become the law, but I s=
till think it=E2=80=99s a good idea.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I would not exactly say that crypto has built =
this system. Lots of entrepreneurs=C2=A0in crypto (1) do conventional thing=
s to make themselves seem stable, conservative and trustworthy and then (2)=
 lose or steal their customers=E2=80=99 money. Still, though, the=C2=A0<em>=
atmosphere=C2=A0</em>in crypto is so suffused with hacks, scams=C2=A0and Po=
nzis that it is=C2=A0<em>hard=C2=A0</em>=E2=80=94=C2=A0not impossible! but =
hard =E2=80=94=C2=A0not to know what you=E2=80=99re getting into. And so, w=
hen a crypto exchange loses its customers=E2=80=99=C2=A0money, the customer=
s=E2=80=99=C2=A0reaction tends to be less =E2=80=9CI can=E2=80=99t believe =
a crypto exchange lost my life savings=E2=80=9D and more=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cwell=
 I put my gambling money there because I=C2=A0thought that it was a <em>rel=
atively</em> trustworthy crypto exchange, but, you know.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway BlockFi Inc. froze customer deposits ea=
rlier this month=C2=A0and filed for bankruptcy yesterday, and=C2=A0Bloomber=
g=E2=80=99s Claire Ballentine and Paulina Cachero dutifully <a href=3D"http=
